─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
WHAT THIS TABLE IS NOT
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

UOM is intentionally minimal. The following concerns present in other
tables do NOT apply here and were not implemented:

- No ChildScopedRows (no line items, no nested records)
- No outbox events (no async workflows triggered on mutation)
- No worker execution (no background processing)
- No reconciliation polling (no eventually-consistent state)
- No soft delete (hard delete only, blocked by link check)
- No audit log (not required at this layer for this table)

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
TEMPLATE NOTES FOR SUBSEQUENT TABLES
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

This table establishes the canonical pattern. When implementing the next
simple table (categories, services, manufacturers, etc.), the following
rules apply:

1. withDatabaseTransaction wraps every use case that performs a
   check-then-write. No exceptions.

2. DB layer functions aggregate raw _count fields into semantic types
   before returning. Application never accesses _count directly.

3. Domain rules (name normalization, delete block logic) live in
   @builders/domain, not inline in use cases.

4. Error class follows UnitOfMeasureExecutionError exactly:
   code, message, status, field?, payload? — plus a companion type guard.

5. Update use cases return getById called within the same transaction
   as the write. Never a separate un-guarded round-trip.

6. The features domain file is a thin re-export layer from @builders/domain.
   No business logic is defined there.
